🧠 PART 1 — What Does “Store in Memory” Mean?

When we say:

Store access token in memory

It simply means:

👉 Store it in a JavaScript variable while the app is running

That’s it.

🔹 Example (Very Simple)
let accessToken = "abc123";

That variable exists:

While the page is open

While the app is running

If you refresh the page:

❌ It disappears.

If you close the tab:

❌ It disappears.

That is what “memory” means.

🔹 In React App Example
const [accessToken, setAccessToken] = useState(null);

When login succeeds:

setAccessToken(response.access_token);

Now it is stored in memory.

When calling API:

fetch("/courses", {
  headers: {
    Authorization: `Bearer ${accessToken}`
  }
});

That’s memory storage.

🔐 Why This Is Safer?

Because:

It is NOT saved to disk

It is NOT accessible after refresh

It reduces attack window

Even if attacker injects JS:

Token disappears when page reloads

🍪 PART 2 — What is a Cookie?

Before HttpOnly, first understand cookie.

A cookie is:

Small data stored by browser and automatically sent with requests to the server.

Example:

Server sends:

Set-Cookie: refresh_token=xyz123

Browser stores it.

After that, whenever you call:

POST /refresh

Browser automatically attaches:

Cookie: refresh_token=xyz123

You do NOT manually attach it.

🔐 What is HttpOnly Cookie?

Normal cookie:

JavaScript CAN read it:

document.cookie

HttpOnly cookie:

JavaScript CANNOT read it.

Even if attacker injects script:

document.cookie

Refresh token will NOT be visible.

That is why it is secure.

🔒 What Does Secure Mean?

If cookie is marked:

Secure

It will only be sent over:

HTTPS

Not HTTP.

🛡 What Does SameSite Mean?

Prevents CSRF attacks.

Options:

Strict → safest

Lax → moderate

None → least secure

🟢 So Final Secure Setup Looks Like This

When user logs in:

Server sends:

Set-Cookie: refresh_token=xyz;
HttpOnly;
Secure;
SameSite=Strict

And JSON:

{
  "access_token": "abc"
}
🔄 Full Flow With Storage
Login:

Access token → stored in memory

Refresh token → stored in HttpOnly cookie

Access API:

Frontend sends:

Authorization: Bearer access_token
Access token expires:

Frontend calls:

POST /refresh

Browser automatically sends refresh cookie.

Server returns new access token.

Frontend updates memory.

🎯 Why This Architecture Is Used

Because:

| Storage         | XSS Risk | Persistent | Safe? |
| --------------- | -------- | ---------- | ----- |
| localStorage    | High     | Yes        | ❌     |
| memory          | Low      | No         | ✅     |
| HttpOnly cookie | Very Low | Yes        | ✅     |

🧠 Interview-Ready Explanation

If interviewer asks:

What does storing in memory mean?

You say:

Storing in memory means keeping the access token in a JavaScript variable or application state while the app is running. It is not persisted to localStorage or cookies, so it disappears on refresh, reducing exposure to XSS attacks.

If they ask:

What is HttpOnly cookie?

You say:

An HttpOnly cookie is a cookie that cannot be accessed via JavaScript. It is automatically sent by the browser with HTTP requests, which makes it ideal for storing refresh tokens securely.

